-- Baker Hughes, Broadwind, Cliffs, King, Peabody, Tenet: U.S. Equity Movers
-- Lu Wang
-- 2010-07-06T20:19:20Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-02/brown-brown-leap-wireless-par-pharmaceutical-cos-u-s-equity-preview.html

          
          
             Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in U.S. trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses,
and prices are as of 4 p.m. in New York.  
 Coal producers advanced after  Cliffs Natural Resources Inc. 
(CLF US), North America’s largest iron-ore producer, said it
will pay $757 million for the West Virginia coal operations of
closely held INR Energy LLC and Banpu Pcl (BANPU TB), Thailand’s
biggest coal producer, agreed to buy the rest of Australia’s
Centennial Coal Co. (CEY AU) for A$2 billion ($1.7 billion).  
 Peabody Energy Corp.  (BTU US) advanced 3.3 percent to
$40.26.  Massey Energy Co.  (MEE US) rose 2.7 percent to $27.02.
 Arch Coal Inc.  (ACI US) added 2.2 percent to $19.74.  Alpha
Natural Resources Inc.  (ANR US) climbed 2.7 percent to $34.17.  
 Cliffs fell 5.1 percent to $44.49.  
 Hospital shares advanced after Barclays Plc said the
industry’s slump since May was “overdone” and now is time to
“become more aggressive” on the group since the companies will
be able to cut costs to offset lower volumes.  
 Tenet Healthcare Corp.  (THC US) rose the most in the
Standard & Poor’s 500 Index, jumping 4.1 percent to $4.32.
 Community Health Systems Inc.  (CYH US) increased 2.4 percent to
$32.21.  
 Baker Hughes Inc.  (BHI US) rose 3.9 percent to $43.93 for
the second-biggest gain in the S&P 500. The oil driller agreed
to sell some assets in the Gulf of Mexico to Superior Energy
Services Inc. (SPN US).  
 Broadwind Energy Inc.  (BWEN US) gained the most in the
Russell 2000 Index, rallying 16 percent to $3.23. The maker of
wind towers said it will supply Gamesa Corporación Tecnológica
SA, a Spanish manufacturer of wind turbine generators, at its
U.S. wind sites.  
 BP Plc  (BP US) jumped 8.7 percent to $31.91, the biggest
gain since June 10. The oil producer said it may intercept the
damaged Macondo well ahead of schedule this month, kicking off a
“kill” process to end the worst oil spill in U.S. history.  
 King Pharmaceuticals Inc.  (KG US) increased 2.2 percent,
the most since June 3, to $7.58. Shares of the drugmaker may
outperform the market by more than 30 percent in the next nine
to 12 months as sales of Embeda, the first tamper-resistant
narcotic approved by U.S. regulators, accelerate in the second
half, Cowen & Co. said in a note.  
 Patterson-UTI Energy Inc.  (PTEN US) rose the most in the
Russell 1000 Index, rallying 6.1 percent to $13.73. The provider
of drilling services to oil and natural gas companies agreed to
buy Key Energy Services Inc.’s (KEG US) pressure pumping and
wireline businesses for about $256.7 million.  
